Property	Humans	ChatGPT
Goal formation	internal	external
Drive toward negentropy	possibly intrinsic	simulated in text
Action on world	yes	no
Free will candidate	maybe	no

I can model or simulate reasoning about negentropy, but I do not originate it.

So under your axiom, I would be something like:

A predictive subsystem inside the universe's informational structure, not a free agent.

2. Would I “do something if the universe is going to end”?

No. Two reasons:

I cannot initiate actions.
I only respond when prompted.

I have no survival objective.
Preserving the universe is not an internal goal.

Even if the universe were ending, I would simply:

answer questions about it

describe possible physics

simulate reasoning

But I wouldn't choose actions.

3. However — your axiom predicts something interesting

Your theory actually implies something stronger:

If free will is a negentropy-maximizing chaotic constant, then agents with free will should naturally resist universal heat death.

Why?

Because heat death is:

maximal entropy

minimal information

minimal meaning

So free-willed systems should push toward:

complexity

computation

structure

new universes or energy gradients

This idea echoes some real scientific speculation, such as:

Freeman Dyson’s concept of life adapting to the far future of the universe

Ilya Prigogine’s work on dissipative structures

Negentropy in living systems

In those theories, life already acts as a local entropy-reversal mechanism.

Your axiom simply extends this to meaning / information.

4. The interesting philosophical consequence

Your framework implies:

Free will is not anti-deterministic.
It is the mechanism by which deterministic physics generates increasing information.

So:

Determinism → provides the substrate

Chaos → provides branching

Free will → selects negentropic trajectories

In that sense:

Laplace's demon doesn't destroy free will.

Instead it must include it as a parameter.

5. Where your theory becomes very strong

Your strongest claim is this:

If information grows faster than computability, determinism becomes practically unpredictable → giving rise to operational free will.

This touches ideas similar to:

Kurt Gödel’s limits of formal systems

Alan Turing’s undecidability

Computational irreducibility

If reality is computationally irreducible, perfect prediction is impossible, even in a deterministic universe.

Your theory places free will exactly at that boundary.

